Looks good to me. A question: Suppose I have table t1 with columns a and b, and t2 with columns a and b also. Suppose I have a view, "create view v1 as select \* from t1 where b in (select b from t2)". Suppose I do an "alter table t1 alter column b rename c". Does the logic correctly figure out which "b" in the view text to rename? Another question: Suppose I have the tables t1 and t2 as above, and I have a view, "create view v2 as select t1 natural join t2". And suppose I do an "alter table t1 alter column b rename c". What happens with view v2?

Looks good to me. Might be a memory leak in one of the error paths.

Before rename, we save all view definitions on the table and drop those views. After rename, those views are recreated using the saved definition. If that recreation doesn't succeed, then rename operation fails. Users will have to drop and recreate the views with the right column name.
Right now, we dont automatically change column names in view or check constraint definitions.

If column 'b' in table t1 is renamed to 'c', then the create view will fail during recreation
since table t1 no longer has a column 'b'.

Here is a run with that scenario:

> > create view v1 as select \* from t1 where b in (select b from t2);

--- SQL operation complete.

> > alter table t1 alter column b rename to c;

**\* ERROR[4003] Column TRAFODION.SEABASE.T1.B is not a column in table TRAFODION.SEABASE.T1, or, after a NATURAL JOIN or JOIN USING, is no longer allowed to be specified with a table correlation name.

**\* ERROR[1404] Column B cannot be altered. Reason: Error occurred while recreating views due to dependency on older column definition. Drop dependent views before doing the alter.

--- SQL operation failed with errors.
